1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:07,021
Today I will show you how ChatGPT can be transformed into real learning tools, not just a translator.

2
00:00:07,102 --> 00:00:14,533
Today I will not speak generally, but will use specific prompts and queries that you will also be able to replicate.

3
00:00:15,033 --> 00:00:18,799
For example, today I will show all of this at the A1 level.

4
00:00:18,779 --> 00:00:20,902
But this video is not just for beginners.

5
00:00:20,922 --> 00:00:25,649
You will be able to adapt all of this for yourselves as well, because we will be building a complete learning system.

6
00:00:26,250 --> 00:00:33,580
And you can find ready-made prompts for your level in the pinned comment under this video on my Telegram channel.

7
00:00:33,600 --> 00:00:35,102
And our first step is the base.

8
00:00:35,243 --> 00:00:39,268
You need to know exactly what English level you have right now.

9
00:00:39,449 --> 00:00:43,875
So it's not okay to write: I'm somewhere between A2 or B1.

10
00:00:43,855 --> 00:00:49,580
You need to know your precise level, because then ChatGPT won't be able to create a program specifically for you.

11
00:00:49,981 --> 00:00:54,045
It will either be something too easy, or too difficult, on the contrary.

12
00:00:54,065 --> 00:01:01,232
For this case, I have a ready-made prompt for you that you can copy and paste into your chat.

13
00:01:01,272 --> 00:01:02,133
I'll read it now.

14
00:01:02,673 --> 00:01:04,755
You are an experienced English language teacher.

15
00:01:05,095 --> 00:01:07,358
Help me determine my English level.

16
00:01:07,798 --> 00:01:13,103
Create a series of tasks that test vocabulary, grammar, reading comprehension, speaking.

17
00:01:13,083 --> 00:01:15,927
And, step-by-step, gradually increasing in difficulty.

18
00:01:16,187 --> 00:01:19,511
After my answers, explain what this means for my level.

19
00:01:19,752 --> 00:01:21,053
And tell me what it is.

20
00:01:21,434 --> 00:01:26,781
And in 20-30 minutes, you will have a real understanding of where you are now and where you need to move next.

21
00:01:27,041 --> 00:01:36,493
And next, another critically important point, a mistake I see constantly: people open too many chats and try to learn in them.

22
00:01:36,513 --> 00:01:42,723
But it is very important to open only one chat and learn specifically in it.

23
00:01:43,324 --> 00:01:46,809
Because then this chat remembers everything about you.

24
00:01:46,829 --> 00:01:54,260
What mistakes you made, what you said wrong, what you've already covered, what needs to be reinforced again.

25
00:01:54,660 --> 00:02:01,450
And when you open new chats, this memory is not saved and you seemingly go through the same thing again.

26
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:05,927
Therefore, we fix one chat, one teacher.

27
00:02:05,947 --> 00:02:07,450
Well then, now our second step.

28
00:02:07,490 --> 00:02:12,698
Now we will create that very teacher who will teach us.

29
00:02:13,279 --> 00:02:17,346
And let's read this prompt, well, you can copy it later.

30
00:02:17,326 --> 00:02:21,831
I am learning English, my level is A1, here you can insert your level.

31
00:02:22,351 --> 00:02:29,419
Teach me like a patient teacher, from simple to complex, in small steps, with constant repetition, without overwhelming.

32
00:02:29,999 --> 00:02:43,333
Work with me in one chat, remember my typical mistakes, return to them later, first explain, then give practice, then repeat, speak simply and clearly.

33
00:02:43,313 --> 00:02:54,668
And with this step, you do a very important thing: you don't just open another random chat, you create your permanent, stable teacher.

34
00:02:54,688 --> 00:03:02,098
Well, you have already created your teacher, you have given him a goal, now we will move on to practice.

35
00:03:02,118 --> 00:03:08,146
In the next step, we need to get some ready-made phrases from him that match our level.

36
00:03:08,386 --> 00:03:09,608
What do we write to him?

37
00:03:10,769 --> 00:03:16,458
Give me 10 very simple English phrases for A1 level on the topic of getting acquainted without grammatical explanations.

38
00:03:17,039 --> 00:03:24,370
Here you can change both the level and the topic for which you want to receive these phrases, but overall, I think the logic is clear.

39
00:03:24,791 --> 00:03:29,718
And look, if he sends us, I'll add a screenshot here, he's sending it right now.

40
00:03:29,938 --> 00:03:33,604
Okay, here are 10 very simple phrases for A1 level on the topic of getting acquainted.

41
00:03:34,715 --> 00:03:39,420
And there's a list: hello, hi, my name is Anna, and so on.

42
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:46,227
In principle, he did his job: he sent you not just words, but complete ready-made phrases.

43
00:03:46,247 --> 00:03:54,075
And I think you should already know that English should be learned not with individual words, but with ready-made language chunks.

44
00:03:54,515 --> 00:03:58,339
The next stage for us will be listening and a prompt for listening.

45
00:03:58,960 --> 00:04:02,023
Read these phrases aloud slowly.

46
00:04:02,243 --> 00:04:04,165
And now I'll show you how it works.

47
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:05,681
Listen.

48
00:04:05,701 --> 00:04:10,106
I will now read them clearly and slowly, so it will be easy for you to repeat.

49
00:04:10,486 --> 00:04:11,447
Ready?

50
00:04:11,467 --> 00:04:11,987
Let's go.

51
00:04:12,588 --> 00:04:13,049
First.

52
00:04:13,409 --> 00:04:14,250
Hello.

53
00:04:14,270 --> 00:04:14,710
Second.

54
00:04:14,971 --> 00:04:15,351
Hi.

55
00:04:15,791 --> 00:04:16,232
Third.

56
00:04:16,252 --> 00:04:17,633
My name is Anna.

57
00:04:18,034 --> 00:04:18,614
Fourth.

58
00:04:18,634 --> 00:04:19,956
I am Anna.

59
00:04:19,976 --> 00:04:20,456
Fifth.

60
00:04:20,816 --> 00:04:21,617
What is your name?

61
00:04:22,078 --> 00:04:22,879
Sixth.

62
00:04:22,899 --> 00:04:24,180
Nice to meet you.

63
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:24,580
Seventh.

64
00:04:24,901 --> 00:04:26,362
I am from Ukraine.

65
00:04:26,382 --> 00:04:26,843
Eighth.

66
00:04:27,203 --> 00:04:28,404
Where are you from?

67
00:04:28,424 --> 00:04:29,265
Ninth.

68
00:04:29,285 --> 00:04:30,346
How are you?

69
00:04:30,366 --> 00:04:30,947
Tenth.

70
00:04:30,967 --> 00:04:32,228
I am fine.

71
00:04:32,208 --> 00:04:36,143
I'll repeat as many times as needed, if necessary, just say so and we will do more.

72
00:04:36,663 --> 00:04:37,885
Like so.

73
00:04:37,905 --> 00:04:39,066
Look, what's important here.

74
00:04:39,126 --> 00:04:40,788
You can listen to this more than once.

75
00:04:40,808 --> 00:04:43,452
Rather, I really advise you to listen to it more than once.

76
00:04:43,812 --> 00:04:44,253
What for?

77
00:04:44,273 --> 00:04:53,425
So that you will fix it in your mind, your brain will process it better and will then be able to recognize it in real language, in real live language.

78
00:04:53,886 --> 00:04:59,794
And it will also be able to then suggest variations of these phrases when you are speaking English yourself.

79
00:04:59,874 --> 00:05:01,856
So listen as much as possible.

80
00:05:02,597 --> 00:05:12,815
By the way, regarding how to listen to all this, I'll add a screenshot here now, showing what you need to click to have what was written voiced.

81
00:05:13,336 --> 00:05:15,400
The next step for us will be reading.

82
00:05:15,961 --> 00:05:21,672
And not just any random reading, but reading exactly what you just worked with.

83
00:05:21,652 --> 00:05:32,587
That is, we will once again polish those phrases and expressions that you have just read and heard, and what prompt we will have for this.

84
00:05:32,888 --> 00:05:33,929
Look.

85
00:05:33,949 --> 00:05:37,033
Let's create a monologue, a story, a text for reading.

86
00:05:37,354 --> 00:05:40,278
A text of six sentences for A1 level with these phrases.

87
00:05:40,739 --> 00:05:50,292
It should sound like natural language, one paragraph, sentences are logically connected, without a list and without separate phrases, so that it can be said in one breath.

88
00:05:50,272 --> 00:05:54,499
And now I'll show you what it created for me.

89
00:05:54,519 --> 00:05:57,083
Here I'm adding a screenshot of its response.

90
00:05:57,443 --> 00:05:58,465
And what to do with this?

91
00:05:58,865 --> 00:06:01,489
You can read this aloud to yourself.

92
00:06:02,811 --> 00:06:04,414
You can do it more than once, even.

93
00:06:04,434 --> 00:06:10,183
You can ask it to voice it again using that button I already showed you.

94
00:06:10,563 --> 00:06:11,445
And what's important here?

95
00:06:11,545 --> 00:06:17,494
That your brain perceives what it has heard before and starts to recall it.

96
00:06:17,474 --> 00:06:44,898
And at this moment you are really learning. And now we're going to move on to grammar. But I'm not going to ask it to write down the rules of use for me now. I'll try to get it to simply explain it to me. And look what we can write to it: Explain very simply what "I am" means, without grammatical terms and complex explanations. Look what it answers me.

97
00:06:45,398 --> 00:06:48,222
I am, I am. This is what you say about yourself.

98
00:06:48,282 --> 00:06:53,969
When you want to say who you are, what you are like, how you feel, you start with I am.

99
00:06:53,989 --> 00:06:55,430
And real-life examples follow.

100
00:06:55,550 --> 00:06:56,952
In my opinion, the explanation is super.

101
00:06:56,972 --> 00:07:00,656
There are no complex terms here, there are no rules, no tenses.

102
00:07:01,157 --> 00:07:06,263
Simply logical, understandable, and initially just wonderful.

103
00:07:06,243 --> 00:07:10,630
Of course, if it's a different level, it will be a bit more complicated.

104
00:07:10,730 --> 00:07:14,336
You'll see all this in the prompt, but for now, the logic is as follows.

105
00:07:14,356 --> 00:07:17,181
Well then, now comes my favorite stage.

106
00:07:17,581 --> 00:07:20,887
The stage when we start talking to our chat.

107
00:07:21,467 --> 00:07:26,576
Again, through this button, we need to switch to conversation mode with it.

108
00:07:26,596 --> 00:07:28,639
And what do we say?

109
00:07:30,205 --> 00:07:35,130
Let's have a simple dialogue in English for A1 level now.

110
00:07:35,771 --> 00:07:41,877
You are a new person to me, and ask me simple questions one by one.

111
00:07:41,897 --> 00:07:43,299
Of course, everything is fine.

112
00:07:43,579 --> 00:07:47,423
Let's start a simple dialogue, and I'll ask questions one by one.

113
00:07:47,924 --> 00:07:48,945
First question.

114
00:07:48,965 --> 00:07:50,827
What is your name?

115
00:07:50,847 --> 00:07:52,549
What is your name?

116
00:07:52,569 --> 00:07:54,711
My name is Anastasia.

117
00:07:57,020 --> 00:07:59,723
Thank you, Anastasia.

118
00:07:59,743 --> 00:08:02,726
Where are you from?

119
00:08:02,987 --> 00:08:06,190
I am from Ukraine.

120
00:08:06,210 --> 00:08:07,372
Good.

121
00:08:07,392 --> 00:08:12,798
What do you like to do in your free time?

122
00:08:13,118 --> 00:08:17,383
I like to cook and work out.

123
00:08:17,403 --> 00:08:18,584
Sounds good.

124
00:08:18,604 --> 00:08:21,087
Can you tell me if you are learning English now?

125
00:08:22,906 --> 00:08:31,878
I think that you got it, that I'm learning English right now.

126
00:08:31,898 --> 00:08:32,318
Absolutely.

127
00:08:32,338 --> 00:08:33,740
I just wanted to hear you say it.

128
00:08:33,760 --> 00:08:36,123
You're doing great.

129
00:08:36,143 --> 00:08:36,363
Keep it up.

130
00:08:36,383 --> 00:08:36,724
Here.

131
00:08:36,924 --> 00:08:38,827
This is roughly how it happens.

132
00:08:39,267 --> 00:08:51,563
Look, if at some stage it says something wrong, you can just give it some clarification regarding that, or ask it to break down the questions one by one, because sometimes it can give them out as a whole list.

133
00:08:52,387 --> 00:09:05,469
But overall, look, the conversation is built wonderfully, you can also ask it, for example, to translate each question or to point out any of your mistakes when you answer, so use it.

134
00:09:05,489 --> 00:09:16,167
And after that, we will practice writing. Yes, you heard right, I always tell everyone: the more you write, the better you speak, so here's a prompt for writing.

135
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:47,227
Help me write three simple sentences about myself in English for A1 level. Now I will show you what it answered me, so look, I'm adding it. First, it wrote me templates that I can use. And then it gives "your turn", meaning for you to write these three sentences to it. In this case, when you write your sentences to it, it will correct you if something is wrong, or on the contrary, praise you if you wrote everything correctly. And now a very important nuance.

136
00:09:47,547 --> 00:09:51,791
After each session, you must record your progress.

137
00:09:51,871 --> 00:09:57,918
You have to help this machine record everything you write to it.

138
00:09:57,958 --> 00:10:00,780
Also, the prompt.

139
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:07,327
Make a short summary of the lesson: what we covered, what mistakes are repeated, to review next time.

140
00:10:08,008 --> 00:10:09,489
Not more than 100 words.

141
00:10:09,509 --> 00:10:21,877
Look, you can insert all of this at the end of this lesson and at the beginning of the next, so you don't forget what you've already covered and can pay attention to what you need to work on better.

142
00:10:22,117 --> 00:10:24,642
And now there will probably be a very logical question from you.

143
00:10:24,742 --> 00:10:27,747
Okay, I practiced today, what should I do next?

144
00:10:27,807 --> 00:10:30,653
How to do all this independently?

145
00:10:30,773 --> 00:10:35,361
And I'll tell you, you don't need to reinvent the wheel, because I've already invented it for you.

146
00:10:36,067 --> 00:10:41,835
You just need to copy this prompt and then follow our already created road map.

147
00:10:41,855 --> 00:10:42,820
Look, what a prompt.

148
00:10:44,099 --> 00:10:46,804
Conduct a daily English lesson for A1 level.

149
00:10:47,265 --> 00:10:48,907
One lesson - one day.

150
00:10:49,208 --> 00:10:50,530
Work step-by-step.

151
00:10:51,031 --> 00:10:55,239
Start with a brief review of what we've already covered – 2-3 minutes.

152
00:10:55,820 --> 00:10:59,967
In the review, use the same words and constructions as before.

153
00:11:00,267 --> 00:11:03,112
After each step, stop and wait for my "next".

154
00:11:03,774 --> 00:11:22,303
Lesson structure: Brief review, brief explanation of the new topic, 8-10 simple phrases (read them aloud), a short coherent text, a simple explanation of the meaning of constructions, a short dialogue, three sentences for writing, speak simply and don't overload.

155
00:11:22,503 --> 00:11:26,349
And that's it, ChatGPT will guide you further as a real teacher.

156
00:11:26,749 --> 00:11:28,652
I think it's just magic.

157
00:11:28,632 --> 00:11:31,976
And regarding these prompts.

158
00:11:32,576 --> 00:11:35,179
They are written for a general learning system.

159
00:11:35,199 --> 00:11:44,690
If you need a specific topic or want to specifically review a grammatical structure and so on, you can, of course, adjust it.

160
00:11:44,710 --> 00:11:45,731
So adapt.

161
00:11:46,111 --> 00:11:56,783
ChatGPT is not a tutor, but with a well-built system, you can create a truly working simulator out of it.

162
00:11:57,893 --> 00:12:05,949
Therefore, the main thing here is to create exactly this system, so that it is not chaotic, but broken down like we did today.

163
00:12:05,969 --> 00:12:08,754
Because that's how our brain will absorb it best.

164
00:12:09,235 --> 00:12:14,285
So, if you found it useful, interesting, and liked it, I would be very grateful for your support.

165
00:12:14,305 --> 00:12:18,433
Like, comment, subscribe.

166
00:12:18,886 --> 00:12:31,458
I want to remind you that under this video and in the pinned comment, you will find a link to my Telegram channel, where all the prompts for each level will be collected.

167
00:12:32,040 --> 00:12:32,541
Bye!

